          "id": 15771,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Temperature of growth was set wrong</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 15772,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Culture media was selective&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 15773,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">E. coli produced colicin that inhibited S. epidermidis growth</span></span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 15774,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Gram positives have more generation time&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">In a laboratory experiment, both Staphylococcus epidermidis and Escherichia coli were cultured on the same media. After overnight incubation, it was observed that only E. coli showed significant growth, while S. epidermidis did not grow at all. What could be the most likely reason for this difference in the growth observed in the culture?</span></span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5957652",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34951,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ans. B) Culture media was selective.&nbsp;</span></span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Option B:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>selective growth of only E. coli </strong>and <strong>not S. epidermidis </strong>suggests that the <strong>culture media used was selective in nature</strong>. <strong>Selective media are designed to suppress the growth </strong>of some <strong>microorganisms while allowing others to grow</strong>, which can be <strong>achieved through the addition of specific agents that inhibit certain bacteria</strong>. In this case, the media might have <strong>contained agents that inhibit </strong>the <strong>growth of Gram-positive bacteria like S. epidermidis</strong>, allowing only <strong>Gram-negative bacteria like E. coli to flourish</strong>.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Explanation:</span></span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option A. Temperature of growth was set wrong</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">:&nbsp; Both <strong>S. epidermidis and E. coli can grow </strong>at a similar range of temperatures.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option C. E. coli produced colicin that inhibited S. epidermidis growth</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">:&nbsp; is a <strong>possibility</strong>, as <strong>colicins are bacteriocins produced by some E. coli strains</strong>. However, their presence and effect would be more specific and not as commonly encountered in a routine lab setting.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Option D</span></span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">. <strong>Gram positives have more generation time </strong>is not a relevant factor in this context; both bacteria can grow well under standard lab conditions.</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Educational Objective:</span></span></u></strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">The <strong>role of selective media </strong>is <strong>demonstrated by the selective growth of Escherichia coli </strong>over <strong>Staphylococcus epidermidis </strong>in a <strong>laboratory setting</strong>. The <strong>media&#39;s selective nature</strong>, possibly <strong>containing agents that inhibit the growth of Gram-positive bacteria like S. epidermidis</strong>, allowing the <strong>growth of Gram-negative bacteria like E. coli</strong>, highlights the importance of choosing appropriate media for culturing different bacterial types.&nbsp;</span></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Aptos,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Ref:&nbsp;</span></span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Apurva Sastry Essentials of Microbiology, pg 31/4e</span></span></strong></span></span></p>",
